But glorious is the fruit of such a dignity: that beeing safe, and out of theyr
• each, they see the envy of other men against them;
and those men forced to give them respect, whom they know maliciously bent, hiding their aemulation, and striving to expresse love. For such envy joyned with admiration, and stirred up onely against felicity, doth yeild (I know not in what sense) a kinde of ambitious pleasure to those men, against whom it rises, as putting them in mind of their owne greatnesse, and the basenesse of other men.
